sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BM-CFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Bacterial-Mammalian promoter with eCFP reporter: BBaK216005 + CArG promoter sequence + BBa_E0420
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Our hybrid promoter hopes to add to the systems already in the registry by creating a hybrid promoter that combines the bacterial promoter PyeaR and the mammalian CArG element , both of which respond to exogenous nitrogenous species. Combining the two would allow a more modular NO sensor that can be used in mammalian and bacterial cells interchangeably. The hybrid promoter has been attached to the reporter: enhanced Cyan Fluorescence Protein (eCFP). The hybrid promoter has been characterised by observing expression of flourescent protein, and found to have increased transcription in response to increasing concentrations of potassium nitrate.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: NRP-UEA-Norwich
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: BBaK216005 + BHN + CArG promoter sequence E9-ns2 + BBa_E0420
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The enhanced Cyan Fluorescence Protein (eCFP) was chosen with the eventual aim of attaching it to part BBa_K774002 or BBa_K774003. It was therefore important that the fluorescence peak of eCFP didn't overlap with RFP too much, as eCFP and RFP will be reporting on either part BBa_K774002 or BBa_K774003 at the same time.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: B-M
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Bacterial-Mammalian Promoter: BBaK216005 + BHN + CArG promoter sequence E9-ns2
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: A hybrid of the PyeaR promoter (BBa_K216005) and the E9-ns2 CArG promoter (Ref:1). Two versions will be synthesised, with the promoters altering their position in relation to the 5???-end of the sequence.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: NRP-UEA-Norwich
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
PyeaR promoter (BBa_K216005) and the E9-ns2 CArG promoter (Ref:1)
Ref1: Scott, S.D., Joiner, M.C. & Marples, B., 2002. Optimizing radiation-responsive gene promoters for radiogenetic cancer therapy. Gene therapy, 9(20), p.1396-402. Available at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12365005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
To provide additional restriction enzyme sites that may become useful during later cloning steps, BamHI, HindIII and NdeI have been added between the 2 promoters.
It is envisaged that any open reading frame (e.g. RFP or GFP) will be cloned ???downstream??? (i.e. at the 3???-end) of these promoter sequences.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
